    {
        "content": "<p>In 2014 Gromov gave a very interesting series of lectures on probability theory (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aJAQVletzdY\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aJAQVletzdY</a>). The slides/notes are here <a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/rbAXXaJOoqmd2_qW613bJj_I/Six-Lectures-on-Probabiliy-Symmetry-Linearity.pdf\">Six-Lectures-on-Probabiliy-Symmetry-Linearity.pdf</a>.</p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"aJAQVletzdY\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aJAQVletzdY\"><img src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/aJAQVletzdY/default.jpg\"></a></div><p>One of his main ideas is that probability theory needs a Grothendieck-style refoundation.<br>\nHe compares Kolmogorov's approach to probability to Weil's approach to algebraic geometry in two ways:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Both are \"manifestly set theoretic\".</li>\n<li>Both rely on an arbitrary absolute domain over which everything takes place (a given probability space in the case of Kolmogorov vs. a given field in the case of Weil).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Gromov states that probability spaces should instead be certain functors from the category  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> = (ﬁnite probability measure spaces and reductions) to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> akin to how schemes are just certain functors from commutative rings to sets.</p>\n<p>There's a lot more there and it's worth watching the lectures (and reading through the notes). My knowledge of probability theory is practically nonexistent so I was curious if anyone knows whether this approach works and whether it's been pursued at all.</p>",
        "id": 217037581,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1605635342
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This looks related to <a href=\"https://drops.dagstuhl.de/opus/volltexte/2017/8051/pdf/LIPIcs-CALCO-2017-1.pdf\">https://drops.dagstuhl.de/opus/volltexte/2017/8051/pdf/LIPIcs-CALCO-2017-1.pdf</a> except I'm not sure what to make of the fact that (based on a quick skim of the notes) Gromov seems to consider covariant functors rather than contravariant ones.</p>",
        "id": 217039060,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1605636022
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well a scheme is a certain functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mtext>Aff</mtext><mtext>op</mtext></msup><mo>→</mo><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Aff}^\\text{op} \\rightarrow \\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Aff</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, but <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Aff</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Aff}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Aff</span></span></span></span></span> is defined to be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mtext>CRing</mtext><mtext>op</mtext></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{CRing}^\\text{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.932062em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">CRing</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.737622em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1362300000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> so Gromov's category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> plays the 'algebraic' role akin to the role  of commutative rings in AG.</p>",
        "id": 217039846,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1605636336
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But compared to Alex Simpson's notes, the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is the full subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> on the finite probability spaces, right?</p>",
        "id": 217040540,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1605636623
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure how to see <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> as on the algebra side rather than the geometry/spatial side. I guess I will need to take a closer look at what Gromov does.</p>",
        "id": 217040685,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1605636705
